00:08:17.420 --> 00:08:22.540
I will try to keep it relatively brief. But I would say one of the biggest tips that I have

00:08:22.540 --> 00:08:28.299
is really think about who your audience is. So, we as data people tend to get really stuck

00:08:28.299 --> 00:08:34.780
in our own use of visualizations when we're analyzing data, when we're thinking about

00:08:35.659 --> 00:08:40.780
what data vis can be used for. We use it a lot in exploratory data analysis, or at least I do.

00:08:40.780 --> 00:08:46.380
And I think it's really easy to think that, oh, well, I understand this chart. So, other people

00:08:46.380 --> 00:08:51.340
will also understand this chart. Whereas actually, most of the time, if we're working with data

00:08:51.340 --> 00:08:56.780
people, we have much more familiarity and expertise and ability to read charts right

00:08:56.780 --> 00:09:02.460
off the bat and understand them than most people do. And so, I think one of my biggest

00:09:02.460 --> 00:09:06.780
tips that we've actually found in research that we've done, but also we just apply practically

00:09:06.780 --> 00:09:11.179
all the time, is that you really have to think about who you're visualizing data for.

00:09:11.739 --> 00:09:17.979
And if that's not a very statsy or data-heavy audience, you might have to actually kind of

00:09:17.979 --> 00:09:23.340
pull back on how complex of a visual you're using or really think carefully about your labels

00:09:24.299 --> 00:09:27.659
and how you're kind of describing the chart and how you're laying it out.

00:09:28.859 --> 00:09:34.299
Putting too much data in one visual can actually just be really overwhelming for some people,

00:09:34.299 --> 00:09:37.659
and they might not even engage with the chart if they look at it and think,

00:09:38.460 --> 00:09:41.179
I'm really going to have to spend some time to figure out what this is saying.

00:09:42.380 --> 00:09:48.059
So, that's one of my biggest things, is just really trying to put yourself in the shoes of

00:09:48.059 --> 00:09:52.700
others. And a great trick for this is asking someone who does not visualize data regularly

00:09:53.340 --> 00:09:59.739
to take a look at your chart and ask if they understand it. I do this all the time with my

00:09:59.739 --> 00:10:05.739
friends. I will send them something and be like, does this make sense? And a lot of times they say,

00:10:05.739 --> 00:10:11.900
no, what are you talking about? And then I fix it. So, that's a really handy approach too,

00:10:11.900 --> 00:10:16.059
is just to lean on people who maybe aren't as in the data space when you're thinking about

00:10:16.059 --> 00:10:21.500
visualizing. I love that. I do this to my husband all the time. He's like, you're making me feel

00:10:21.500 --> 00:10:27.179
dumb. I'm like, no, no, no. If you feel dumb, the visualization is wrong, and it is my fault.

00:10:27.179 --> 00:10:32.140
