00:11:31.419 --> 00:11:36.219
those? And maybe that's through DataVis or just using different words, things like that.

00:11:37.260 --> 00:11:42.219
Yeah, another great question. There are a lot of challenges. I think in particular with

00:11:42.219 --> 00:11:47.659
statistical results, people don't necessarily understand what something like significance means,

00:11:47.659 --> 00:11:53.739
or if we're thinking about a statistical model, it's not just what any individual coefficient is

00:11:53.739 --> 00:11:58.059
that matters. It's really, you know, the model as a whole. And that's something that's really,

00:11:58.059 --> 00:12:04.539
really hard to communicate. So again, it'll be a little bit of a repeat, but one of the things I do

00:12:05.820 --> 00:12:11.580
when we're trying to communicate like something from an actual model or a test or some sort of

00:12:11.580 --> 00:12:15.900
finding is run it past people that aren't statisticians. They might still be researchers,

00:12:16.940 --> 00:12:24.859
but that don't necessarily, you know, think in statistics language and see whether they

00:12:24.859 --> 00:12:31.820
understand what we're trying to say. The other thing I've also tried to do is just not go

00:12:31.820 --> 00:12:38.940
too overboard with communicating significance, right? So there's, I know there's like a million

00:12:38.940 --> 00:12:44.859
different discussions that have been had in the past about practical versus statistical

00:12:44.859 --> 00:12:52.299
significance. And specifically what I do, a lot of it is very public facing, like public policy type

00:12:52.299 --> 00:12:56.700
research. And so for that, there is a difference between, you know, when we're showing

00:12:57.659 --> 00:13:02.460
some sort of summaries of something we tested in a survey, you know, people's opinions about

00:13:02.460 --> 00:13:09.099
something. Does it really matter if percentages are, if we've like really tested that they're

00:13:09.099 --> 00:13:13.659
significantly different across groups, or do we just really want to show, you know,

00:13:13.659 --> 00:13:19.020
what those percentages are and some uncertainty around those estimates, whether or not they might

00:13:19.020 --> 00:13:25.020
be statistically significantly different. So I think it's kind of a two pronged, like thinking

00:13:25.020 --> 00:13:30.859
about whether the actual stat pieces are really, really important to communicate to your audience.

00:13:30.859 --> 00:13:40.619
And then if they are checking with people who like don't speak stat fluently and seeing how we

00:13:40.619 --> 00:13:46.059
can maybe like update the language to make it a little bit more clear. But p-values, for example,

00:13:46.059 --> 00:13:51.820
are notoriously very difficult to communicate to people. And I don't think we've really come up

00:13:51.820 --> 00:13:57.979
with a great solution, but I think just trying to kind of wordsmith the language and even like

00:13:57.979 --> 00:14:03.419
asking our communications people, like, can we iterate on what a better way to say this is,

00:14:03.419 --> 00:14:10.140
that's still faithful to what it actually means statistically, but isn't, you know, our standard

