they're like, you're faster than Googling it, and I'm like, okay, well, that's great. You could

00:45:18.699 --> 00:45:23.580
have just Googled it, but like, you know, I'm happy to answer the question, but I never would

00:45:23.580 --> 00:45:28.219
have, like, thought that that's where I would be when I started, so I think just give yourself

00:45:28.219 --> 00:45:34.860
some grace to just start small and, like, learn whatever system you want to start with and just

00:45:34.860 --> 00:45:39.820
play around with lots of different data. TidyTuesday is a great, great thing for that. It

00:45:39.820 --> 00:45:43.899
just gives you lots of opportunities to try visualizing in different ways and getting

00:45:43.899 --> 00:45:48.699
creative, even if it's just recreating what someone else made. Like, that's really good

00:45:48.699 --> 00:45:54.379
practice, actually, is, like, can I exactly recreate what someone else already did, and it

00:45:54.379 --> 00:46:01.260
takes some of the stress of having to make the decisions for yourself and helps you learn a

00:46:01.260 --> 00:46:06.620
little bit more how to actually just do it, and then once you get more comfortable with, okay, I

00:46:06.620 --> 00:46:11.500
know by heart how to make a stacked bar chart, how to make a bar chart, how to make a line chart, how

00:46:11.500 --> 00:46:16.540
to make a parallel sets diagram, like, whatever you want to make, once you know those, then you

00:46:16.540 --> 00:46:21.979
start getting more comfortable with when you see new data, which way should it be visualized and

00:46:21.979 --> 00:46:29.500
sort of making that choice for yourself. I love that. I absolutely agree. TidyTuesday, if you

00:46:29.500 --> 00:46:35.899
have not explored it, it's just a GitHub repo. It's very approachable. I know that there has

00:46:35.899 --> 00:46:39.979
